<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1340,1567]" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">
Described from Mysore in 
<collectingRegion box="[443,552,1405,1428]" country="India" name="Karnataka" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Karnataka</collectingRegion>
State, this species is also recorded in 
<collectingCountry box="[963,1018,1405,1428]" name="India" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">India</collectingCountry>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1085,1212,1405,1428]" country="India" name="Tamil Nadu" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Tamil Nadu</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1266,1401,1405,1428]" country="India" name="West Bengal" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">West Bengal</collectingRegion>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tyagi, K. &amp; Kumar, V." box="[151,431,1440,1463]" pageId="2" pageNumber="449" pagination="64 - 98" refId="ref2007" refString="Tyagi, K. &amp; Kumar, V. (2016) Thrips (Insecta: Thysanoptera) of India - An Updated Checklist. Halteres, 7, 64 - 98." type="journal article" year="2016">Tyagi and Kumar (2016)</bibRefCitation>
. Specimens in the Natural History Museum, London, from these Indian States have been studied, and these were taken from coffee with “diseased leaves” or specifically in association with 
<emphasis box="[1230,1429,1473,1497]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="449">Hemileia vastatrix</emphasis>
. The field observations quoted above from Timor Leste suggest that this thrips is probably dependent on this rust fungus for its life history.
</paragraph>
